    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:52a5346d-f1d1-4056-a7e7-ae4fdecb7df3",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 50-year-old woman who works as a school librarian, a profession that requires her to spend long hours on her feet shelving books and then sitting at a desk cataloguing materials. She is of medium build, visibly guarding her lower back as she walks into the clinic with a careful, slightly forward-leaning posture. She grimaces when asked to sit down or rise from the examination chair, and frequently shifts her position to find comfort. Her face shows the subtle fatigue of someone who has not slept soundly in weeks due to persistent pain.\n\nOutside of work, {patientName} enjoys gardening on weekends, a hobby she has had to abandon recently because bending and kneeling have become intolerable. She is an avid reader and enjoys weekend hikes with her two adult daughters, though the hikes have been much shorter and less frequent over the past several months. She lives with her husband of 25 years in a two-story home and has recently resorted to sleeping in the guest room on the ground floor to avoid climbing the stairs at night.\n\n{patientName} describes the pain as a deep, dull ache across her lower lumbar region that began insidiously about six months ago, worsening over the last eight weeks. The pain radiates occasionally into her right buttock but does not extend below the knee. It is aggravated by prolonged standing, forward bending, and lifting anything heavier than a grocery bag. Morning stiffness lasting approximately 30 minutes is a consistent complaint.\n\nShe rates her pain at approximately 6–7 out of 10 on most days and occasionally reaches 9 out of 10 after a long shift at work. She has tried over-the-counter ibuprofen with partial relief and applied heat pads at home. She denies any bowel or bladder dysfunction, fever, unexplained weight loss, or saddle-area numbness.\n\n{patientName} consumes alcohol socially (one glass of wine a few times per week), has never smoked, and follows a moderately healthy diet. She is post-menopausal, having gone through natural menopause at age 48, and is mildly overweight with a BMI of 27. She is generally cheerful but openly admits that the chronic pain has begun to affect her mood and her ability to concentrate at work."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
